That standard is usually called "plausibility." Which is why Harry
Turtledove and SM Stirling find their work so roundly trashed here.
Potboilers with some funny historical search and replace--Turtledove--
and swashbuckling imperial racism--Stirling--do not an interesting
thing make.

That's also why people have stopped doing "What if You Wake up as x?"
because, well, boring.

The point is not to discourage ideas; it's to raise the overall
quality of the group. If you've noticed, V's recent post "What if
Cromwell were more like Robespierre?" has gotten several constructive
criticisms, while being silly on its face.

A group with a higher level of overall play--like Doug Muir's taking
control of "Long Live Lancaster" and turning it into a timeline--means
