all of the essays, IIRC, describe ways in which Europe could have
avoided WWI. The ones that fall out of that category are the Lincoln
one, the Bacon one, the Byron one, and maybe the one about a Jacobite
victory. Which isn't to indict any of these in particular. They're not
bad as a means of intellectual laziness, but as a means of their
underlying goal or intention; they all seem to aim for the elimination
of the "Great War" from history.

