In the year 2017, Ray Speer weeps over his  breakfast. Speer once
featured eggs in his morning meal, but egg consumption dwindled
(starting in the 1970s) and were no longer available to people in North
America, Just like dairy products (diminishing since 1960s), eggs had
been dropped by grocery stores because so few people tried to purchase
them.

Ray also remembers newspapers (in decline since the Eighties).  He had a
friend mail him copies of the present _New York Times_, but it had only
been  a twenty page newsheet of  want ads, date resumes, crossword
puzzles and sudoku.  More and more, Ray agrees with the decision of the
_Omaha World Herald_ to cease publication in 2010, If the circulation is
no longer enough to practice real journalism, it is time for the paper
to throw in the towel.

Ray goes to the basement. In long white boxes, Ray has complete runs of
comics, which ceased publication circa 1988  (following the predictions
of just about all comics fans), Ray finds it hard to believe that comics
are obsolete, just like wargaming, American automobiles, quality TV
drama, Westerns, the ACLU, the NAACP,  optimistic science fiction and
the Fred McMurray Fan Club.

There is a TV set, dusty in the corner, next to Ray's collection  of
Mark Grunewald's work  in _Captain America_.  Does that still work?
thinks Ray, as he turns on WebTV. There is still a hot button
connecting him directly to Social History What If?

There are  three posts on SHWI

WANNA SCREW MY SISTER?

GIGANTIC STUPENDOUS SCHLONG!

The third entry is  20,000 lines of poisonous invective, insulting as
insane, perverted, stupid, boring, ridiculous and constipated anyone who
wants to post alternative history scenarios on topics more recent than
the Thirty Years War.

The Censors of SHWI fed upon each other once the group was abandoned by
alt-historians.  Deprived of their natural prey, each of them accused
peers of insanity, crimes, and low quality posts. The Censors had
triumphed though --- there were no posts they could object to because
there were no posts at all . . . . .

==========COMMENTARY===========

C'mon folks. A decline of  volume in X does not lead to the extinction
of X, as my  dreary little scenario postulates.

For thirty years, I have been told regularly that my fellow comic geeks
and I are doomed Dodos, fans of an art form that peaked in the  freaking
Nineteen Forties. Nature will no longer replenish our numbers so we must
compel our neighbors, pals and relatives to acquire our habit. If we are
that badly off, it is amazing that I can still find comics shops filled
with freshly printed comics and free spending patrons.

Likewise with SHWI.  It will be around.

