super-villain makes a big heist, (b) super-villain attempts a second
heist, fails but escapes without the loot and (c) Batman catches
him/her on the third attempted heist.

One of my favorite stories involved the super-villain who got caught
because he did his crimes disguised as Batman (which of course caused
endless grief with Commissioner Gordon since Batman was the last
person the Commissioner would expect to be robbing banks) but got
caught because he had been in prison for 7 years and did not know
Batman had changed his uniform by adding the searchlight yellow oval
behind the bat to his logo...I also recall often enjoying the second
story in the Detective comic better than the lead Batman story.

For the LSH I almost cried when they killed off Ferro Lad.

(For the non-cognoscenti that was roughly 1969-72)

I also had a HUGE collection of Charles Schulz's Peanuts annuals and
still do have my complete set of Len Norris cartooon annuals.

Norris of course was the leading political cartoonist for the
Vancouver Sun starting from the early 1950s to the mid-1980s. He was
definitely one of the 2 or 3 top Canadian political cartoonists of the
era and features prominently in the Editorial Cartoons Collection of
Simon Fraser University which can be found at
http://edocs.lib.sfu.ca/projects/Cartoons/

This site I recommend to anyone who loves political cartoons even if
they don't know a thing about Canadian politics.
